{"cursor":"2239","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Bungo Yoshida' (May 3, 1934 – January 16, 2008) was a Japanese puppeteer,\nwho built a whole new audience for the traditional puppetering form of\n[[bunraku]] by combining it with rock music.\n\nBorn as 'Teruo Takahashi' in 1934, Yoshida was initiated into the Bunraku\ntheatre as a disciple of Tamagoro Yoshida II in 1951, changing his name to\n'Kotama Yoshida'. For twenty years, he performed mostly female roles, until\nswitching to male roles in the 1970s. Concerned by falling audience numbers and\na lack of young people taking up bunraku, Yoshida combined the ancient art form\nwith his love of rock music, which he combined for a 1980 adaptation of [[The\nLove Suicides at Sonezaki]] (Sonezaki ShinjÅ«) with the music written and\nperformed by Japanese rock musician Ryudo Uzaki, and occasionally with a live\norchestra. [http://www.abc.net.au/news/stories/2008/01/17/2140418.htm\nJapanese puppeteer Yoshida dies], Australian Broadcasting Corporation, January\n17, 2008.\n\nHe was formerly married to the American television personality and essayist\nEdith Hanson. Yoshida died at his home in Osaka on January 16, 2008 after\nsuffering from liver\ncancer. [http://www.breitbart.com/article.php?id=D8U6TUQ80&show_article=1\n'Bunraku' theater puppeteer Yoshida Bungo dies at 73+], [[Andrew\nBreitbart|breitbart.com]], January 16, 2008.\n","linknr":111,"url":"Bungo_Yoshida","recorded":1374967303,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Bungo_Yoshida&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Bungo_Yoshida&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cs